Research Topic: The Factors Associated with Suicide Rates¶

Group Blackcurrant: Wenxin Zhou, Junpeng Jiang, Zuxuan Huai, Lijia Liu

Introduction: Background information¶

Mental health is very important to all of us in our fast-paced life. Many NGOs and schools are holding a lot of activities in promoting a healthy mental state. When we browsing data on Kaggle, one data about suicide rates caught our eyes. We are very interested in suicide rates, which is severe mental health to the extreme.

Supposedly, people in developed countries should be in a good economic state and should have good lives. On the other hand, we think that these developed countries also encourage individuality and people are likely to be open about suicides. We would like to take a deeper look at the data to find out what factors are associated with suicide rates. The dataset has suicide and economic records from 101 countries for different ages and generations. a statistic composite index of life expectancy, education, and per capita income indicators, which are used to rank countries into four tiers of human development.

Variables in our dataset includes:

  • Year
  • Country
  • Age
  • Sex: Female & Male
  • Suicide Rates: suicides/100k population
  • GDP
  • GDP per capita
  • HDI: a statistic composite index of life expectancy, education, and per capita income indicators, which are used to rank countries into four tiers of human development.
  • Generations: people born in
    • 2000 to present: Generation Z.
    • 1980 to 2000: Millennials
    • 1965 to 1979: Generation X.
    • 1946 to 1964: Boomers.
    • 1925 to 1945: Silent Generation.
    • 1900 to 1924: G.I. Generation.

Because the entire dataset has worldwide data and is hard to find insights, we want to narrow down our research area into two regions. We want to compare regions where we normally associated with good social welfare and peaceful life, and where with political conflicts and constant wars. We choose middle east and northern Europe as these two regions and select five countries with the largest population within these two regions.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

We download our dataset from Kaggle, and the variables in the dataset are : country,year,sex,age,suicide number, population, suicides/100k pop,gdp, gsp per capita, generation and HDI. The HDI data is not complete in our dataset so we find more official data and implement them into our dataset. Then we have HDI data from 1990 to 2017. For further analysis of suicide, we use suicide rate to represent suicides/100k pop.

In [94]:
total = pd.read_csv('master.csv')
HDIdata = pd.read_csv('HDI.csv')
HDIdata = HDIdata.melt('Country')
HDIdata.rename(columns = {'variable':'year', 'value':'HDI', ' gdp':'gdp'}, inplace=True)
HDIdata['year'] = HDIdata.year.astype(int)
HDIdata['Country'] = HDIdata['Country'].str[1:]
HDIdata.head()
total = total.rename(columns = {'suicides/100k pop':'suicide_rate'})
total = total.rename(columns = {'gdp_per_capita':'gdpc'})
total = total.rename(columns = {' gdp':'gdp'})
#total['age'] = total['age'].astype('category')
#total = total.rename_categories({'5-14 years','15-24 years','25-34 years','35-54 years','55-74 years','75+ years'})
total = total.drop(columns='HDI')
total = pd.merge(total, HDIdata,  how='left', left_on=['country', 'year'], right_on = ['Country', 'year'])
total = total.drop(columns='Country')
total.rename(columns = {'HDI_y':'HDI'}, inplace=True)
total.head()

Middle East¶

The paired plots give a general view of the distribution of gdp, gdpc, HDI and suicide rate , it also reflects how different variables are related to each other.¶

  • From the plots we can see the gdp, gdpc show positively relationship with HDI.

  • The first bin of suicide rate are extremely high, in the following analysis we find that there are lots of zeros and there are some other factors that may leads to the zeros.

  • In addition, the plots for suicide rate and other variables seems like a cluster of random points and do not have a trend. This may caused the fact that for each year and each country, there are several replications of these values due to age group and gender.

  • Since gdp is not standardized, we choose to use gdpc instead of gpd in the following analysis.

Exploratory Analysis Summary¶

  • Overall there exist significant distinction of suicide rate between Middle East and North Europe, each represented by 5 countries. North Europe has higher suicide rate than in Middle East

Categorical¶

  • In terms of categorical variables: gender: we see that in both regions, males has significantly higher suicide rate than female. Since in each country the data takes the same number of males and females, the number of men and women is not an indicator of the difference in suicide rate.

  • In both age and generation, the boxplots are consistent with the difference in suicide rates between two regions. For almost all individuals in every age or generation group, North Europe has higher suicide rate in general.

Numeric¶

  • In North Europe, HDI and GDP per capital both have negative relationship with suicide rates. However in middle east, the relationship between HDI,GDP and suicide rate is case-sensitive. For example in Israel, the relationship of HDI, GDP and suicide rate is similar to those in North Europe. One possible explanation is that Israel is the only developed country in Middle east, the way country economy interact with people's benefits may be very similar to countries in Europe.

Insights on Modeling¶

  • Since some factors interact differently, we separately construct models for two regions. We mainly analysis age, gender, generation, HDI and gdp per capital as predictors, and suicide rate as response variable.

Data Modeling¶

We find that HDI seems to have a similar trend, so plot the scatterplot of HDI and GDPC to see their general trend.

Before modeling, we would to have a look a the suicide rate variable.

From the histogram, we find that there are a lot of numbers are zero. Zero suicide rate may be a country really has a low suicide rate, or the value could be missing and just reported as zero for the country to look good. So we counted the number of zeros for each country and made a choropleth map graph to give us a better visualization.

The choropleth map graph gives a better visualization of the countries where there are many zeros in the dataset. We think that 0 suicide rates is really hard to achieve and this graph and the table above show that certain countries indeed have many zeros. So in the modeling part, we decide to fit models both with and without zeros.

Middle East OLS analysis: First, we build a simple liner model with all the mentioned variables to see the effect of each of them on suicide rate by region. By fitting a linear model for middle east, we have seen that not all "age" have p-values below 5% significant level. For the insignificant levels, we revisited the boxplots from data exploration and applied grouping by similar mean and variance. For example, in age group, 15-24, 25-34 and 35-54 exhibits similar spread. Therefore, these groups are combined to a larger group for the model. After we have done such data modification base on the summary output from our model, cross validation is used to further aid our analysis. Applying cross validation at 70-30 split to compare the effect of our data modification and variable selection, we manage to bring the MSE down to 0.2717. From the QQplot,we can find it's normal, but residual plot is not better.

From here we remove rows where suicide rate is 0.¶

Why there are many zeros:¶

We look up the country Bahrain, which has the highest number of 0. Research shows that available data of Bahrain is very limited, and Bahrain is a Islamic country. One of Islam religious faith is prohibit suicide. So we think this also helps decrease the suicide rates in Bahrain. In addition, more research is needed on the epidemiology of suicide risk factors in ethnic groups for further prevention and intervention. Thus, for countries have many zero suicide rates, we need to do more background research.

Analysis: To further explore the possible effects, we build both linear and generalized linear model with only observations with non-zero suicide rate in Northern Europe. Not surprisingly, similar conclusion can be drawn where the same subset of predictors is significant. In addition to those predictors, "HDI" is significant. Although "generation Z" become significant, due to the small number of observation, we ignore it. As such, from these models, we are confident with our analysis on the variables that can significantly influence suicide rate in middle east. From the QQplot and residual plot, we find these models are better than the models of not remove zero.

Conclusion & Reflection¶

Generally, age, gender, generation, GDP per capita as well as HDI are all significant predictors of suicide rate. But in different areas, they may have different effect.

Since gender, age, HDI and GDPC are all significant factors in our analysis. In order to decrease suicide rates, there are many things we could do. We should promote gender equality to avoid stereotypes such as men should suppress emotions. We should also advocate care for mental health and improve accessibility of therapies. Since the elders have high suicide rates, the society should care more about retired people and make sure they are economically grounded. Countries can also develop social standard to achieve higher HDI and GDPC.

Reflections:

  • We only analyzed five countries from each region, and these countries are pretty small. We could increase our data to more countries to get more detailed analysis.
  • There are many factors such as religion, belief, social changes, and social opinions about suicides and access to mental health assistance are now included in this dataset. In order to get a holistic view about that's truly behind suicides, much more research need to be done.
  • When we remove 0s for modeling, the r-square may increase, but the completeness of the data is sacrificed.
